huntBios.GENERAL_INFORMATION:
This unit is comprised primarily of sagebrush in the lower elevations, transitioning into juniper woodlands. The higher elevations have serviceberry, snowberry and bitterbush, with pockets of chokecherry, aspen and conifer. This unit is primarily the Sheeprock and Simpson Mts. This area is very accessible, with many dirt roads. Spend some time in the area to become familiar with the steep terrain, access points and the quality of bucks. Because this is a desert unit, precipitation affects antler growth a lot from one year to the next. If you hope to get away from other hunters you will need to go places ATV’s can’t go.
This area is patrolled quite frequently by DWR personnel. Keep this in mind when you are transporting your game. Try to make it easy to access the permit and tag on the animal.
huntBios.SAFETY_CONS: This is a remote location with some areas with limited access.  Cellular phone coverage is very spotty on this hunt unit.  Digital cell phones may show several bars but cannot always connect due to the distance to the cell towers.  Satellite phones do work in the area.  The biologist suggests hand held radios and even a "Spot Tracker" or “In-reach” type of satellite messaging device for safety.  Make sure someone knows where you plan to camp and when you will return.
huntBios.WEATHER_CONS: The weather on this hunt unit can vary dramatically during the hunting season.  Be prepared for rain, lightning, snow, wind and heat.  Thunderstorms can cause muddy road conditions and rare flash floods in this region.  Most hunters struggle with keeping their harvest meat cool.  Plan on hot weather and plan accordingly.
huntBios.MANAGEMENT_OBJ: 31.3~11200 (entire West Desert unit)~7000 (entire West Desert unit)~25–35~33.5~~~~~~~~For more detailed information on population and objective data please see the Big Game Annual Report Page.
huntBios.BIOLOGIST_NOTES:
Most of the deer are found on the Sheeprock and Simpson Mountains. Few deer are on Desert and Keg Mountains during the hunting season. The average buck harvested on this unit is a 24” wide four point, which means half the bucks harvested are smaller than this. A hunter will have to spend a lot of time and effort to harvest a buck larger than 25” wide. Most of the deer are associated with mountain brush (buckbrush) communities, including serviceberry and snowberry. Concentrate your efforts in the highest elevations and near water sources. Deer can also be found in agricultural areas, written permission is needed to hunt these areas. Most archery hunters are able to locate 20 or more bucks a day.
This unit could experience a wide range of weather events. If it snows I would still expect bucks to remain higher in elevation.

huntMaster.HARVEST_REPORTING: REQUIRED: click here or call 1-800-221-0659 to report your harvest. You must report your harvest, even if you did not take an animal, within 30 days of the season end date that is printed on your permit; failure to do so may result in you not being able to apply for big game species in subsequent years. Submitting teeth or other biological samples from your animal, or having your animal checked by a DWR representative or CWMU operator does NOT fulfill your mandatory harvest reporting requirement.

huntBoundaryInfos.LAND_OWNERSHIP: The majority of land is managed by the BLM and Forest Service. There is private land as well and some of it is accessible through the DWR’s Walk-in-Access Program (https://wildlife.utah.gov/fishing/walk-in-access.html/).
huntBoundaryInfos.WMA_IN_UNIT: There are no WMA's in this unit.
huntBoundaryInfos.CAMPGRND_INFO:
There are many dispersed camping sites within this unit. There are campgrounds located at Vernon Reservoir and Simpson Springs.
Please direct all questions regarding maps and camping regulations to:
Salt Lake BLM Field Office - http://www.blm.gov/office/salt-lake-field-office
USFS- http://www.fs.usda.gov/activity/uwcnf/recreation/camping-cabins
huntBoundaryInfos.PRIM_ACCESS_PTS: Benmore Road, Cherry Creek Road, Pony Express Road, Jericho Junction, Brushwellman Road.
huntBoundaryInfos.SUGGESTED_MAPS: USGS or BLM version 1:100,000 Maps: Lynndyl, Delta, Fish Springs, Rush Valley.
huntBoundaryInfos.COUNTY_ROAD_INFO: most of the roads found on this unit are improved gravel/dirt roads.
huntBoundaryInfos.ATV_VEH_ACCESS: There are numerous roads on this unit. Please stay on the roads. Habitat loss effects all wildlife.
huntBoundaryInfos.PRIV_TRIBE_LAND_ISSUES:
Hunters may notice many areas where juniper trees have been cut down. These activities are to improve wildlife habitat for mule deer and sage-grouse and will have a long-term positive impact.
There are few private ranches that post their property. There are also privately owned lands that allow access or are enrolled through the DWR Walk-in-Access Program. Please be familiar with Utah trespass laws and always be considerate when accessing private lands. Private land is critical to this unit, please stay on the roads, close gates and do not harass livestock.
huntBoundaryInfos.BOUNDARY_DESCRIPTION: Juab, Millard and Tooele counties—Boundary begins at SR-36 and the Pony Express road; south on SR-36 to US-6; southwest on US-6 to SR-174 (the IPP road); northwest on SR-174 to the Dugway Valley road; north on this road to the Pony Express road; northeast on this road to SR-36. USGS 1:100,000 Maps: Lynndyl, Delta, Fish Springs, Rush Valley. Boundary questions? Call the Springville office, 801-491-5678.
